\f0\fs24 \cf0 Quantification of fluorescence intensities:\
\
To quantify the average fluorescence intensity of various antibodies in the nuclei of hair cells, we use an automated method for image segmentation, followed by manual labelling of cells according to their polarity. The regions within which the fluorescence intensity is measured (ROIs) are obtained by first segmenting the hair cells from stainings of a cell type marker and then segmenting the nuclei within them. For neuromasts expressing beta-actin GFP under the hair-cell-specific myo6b promotor for example, the area on each slice occupied by hair cells is segmented from anti-GFP stainings, followed by a segmentation of nuclei within this region using the corresponding DAPI stainings. In a second step, the polarity corresponding to each nucleus is identified manually from the actin stainings (beta-actin or phalloidin), and a manual correction step is applied to the nuclear ROIs to remove any non-nuclear regions. This procedure yields an average of 8 - 20 ROIs per nucleus depending on the experiment, from which a datapoint is obtained by calculating the average intensity across all ROIs, normalized to the average DAPI intensity.\
The processing and analysis were performed with custom ImageJ extensions written in Python. The details of the procedure and the corresponding code are provided at https://github.com/AAAA.\
